03948nam a22006615i 9780292799011DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927990117 a10.7560/7523752doi  a(DE-B1597)588020  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPA4217.E5bM57 2000 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a885/.0100aIsocrates I. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tThe Works of Isocrates -- tAcknowledgments -- tSeries Introduction -- tIntroduction to Isocrates -- tPART ONE -- tPART TWO -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the fourth volume in the Oratory of Classical Greece series. Planned for publication over several years, the series will present all of the surviving speeches from the late fifth and fourth centuries B.C. in new translations prepared by classical scholars who are at the forefront of the discipline. These translations are especially designed for the needs and interests of today's undergraduates, Greekless scholars in other disciplines, and the general public. Classical oratory is an invaluable resource for the study of ancient Greek life and culture. The speeches offer evidence on Greek moral views, social and economic conditions, political and social ideology, and other aspects of Athenian culture that have been largely ignored: women and family life, slavery, and religion, to name just a few. This volume contains works from the early, middle, and late career of the Athenian rhetorician Isocrates (436-338). Among the translated works are his legal speeches, pedagogical essays, and his lengthy autobiographical defense, Antidosis. In them, he seeks to distinguish himself and his work, which he characterizes as "philosophy," from that of the sophists and other intellectuals such as Plato. Isocrates' identity as a teacher was an important mode of political activity, through which he sought to instruct his students, foreign rulers, and his fellow Athenians. He was a controversial figure who championed a role for the written word in fourth-century politics and thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., GreekvTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aGagarin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMirhady, David C.1 aMirhady, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToo, Yun Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToo, Yun Lee.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75237540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799011423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799011/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK